WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:01.079 --> 00:00:02.520
&gt;&gt; Male Interviewer: Thanks everybody for
joining us.

00:00:02.520 --> 00:00:07.330
I am very honored
to have today for a conversation about his

00:00:07.330 --> 00:00:11.019
latest book,
uh, William Patry, known to us here at Google

00:00:11.019 --> 00:00:14.660
as Bill,
who serves as a senior copyright counsel at

00:00:14.660 --> 00:00:18.670
Google,
and before that, has a very esteemed career

00:00:18.670 --> 00:00:23.820
as a copyright scholar, a copyright lawyer,
and in fact, is one of the authors

00:00:23.820 --> 00:00:27.220
of one of the leading treatises on copyright
law,

00:00:27.220 --> 00:00:31.240
'Patry on Copyrights', so thanks very much
for joining us today, Bill.

00:00:31.240 --> 00:00:32.640
&gt;&gt;Bill Patry: Thanks for having me, Fred.

00:00:32.640 --> 00:00:35.400
I was,
had a long and checkered career.

00:00:35.400 --> 00:00:38.450
My mother wondered if I'd
ever be able to keep a job.

00:00:38.450 --> 00:00:39.450
[laughter]

00:00:39.450 --> 00:00:41.280
&gt;&gt;Fred: Lo and behold, it worked out in the
end.

00:00:41.280 --> 00:00:42.280
&gt;&gt;Bill: It did.

00:00:42.280 --> 00:00:43.280
&gt;&gt;Fred: Great!

00:00:43.280 --> 00:00:46.760
So, um, thanks to you
for coming by Google to talk about your new

00:00:46.760 --> 00:00:48.090
book,
How to Fix Copyright.

00:00:48.090 --> 00:00:50.040
It came out just a few
months ago, right?

00:00:50.040 --> 00:00:51.500
&gt;&gt;Bill: Yes, in November.

00:00:51.500 --> 00:00:54.010
&gt;&gt;Fred: Fantastic, and so, we'll have a conversation
here.

00:00:54.010 --> 00:00:57.080
I have some questions to warm Bill up with
and then we'll

00:00:57.080 --> 00:00:58.960
take some questions from the audience.

00:00:58.960 --> 00:01:01.510
I just ask you,
before you ask a question, to wait for the

00:01:01.510 --> 00:01:05.640
handheld mic
so that we have that, uh, on the tape.

00:01:05.640 --> 00:01:11.690
Uh, so, as I was reading your book, Bill,
I kept, I couldn't help but feel I was reading,

00:01:11.690 --> 00:01:13.720
it was almost like a sports account.

00:01:13.720 --> 00:01:17.550
I almost felt like
here was somebody who loves his hometown team

00:01:17.550 --> 00:01:21.200
of copyright,
and yet is deeply unhappy with the direction

00:01:21.200 --> 00:01:23.210
the managers have been taking it.

00:01:23.210 --> 00:01:25.430
Um, so, what do you think about that?

00:01:25.430 --> 00:01:29.460
How how far astray do you think
things have gotten and have you given up hope

00:01:29.460 --> 00:01:32.200
on the, uh,
copyright law that you've spent your life

00:01:32.200 --> 00:01:33.200
working on?

00:01:33.200 --> 00:01:34.520
&gt;&gt;Bill: Nice, that's a pretty good metaphor.

00:01:34.520 --> 00:01:37.810
I mean,
another one would be, it's like a favorite

00:01:37.810 --> 00:01:42.740
aunt or
uncle, you know, who's always been a bit goofy,

00:01:42.740 --> 00:01:48.100
um, maybe a bit creative, but never as creative
as they think they are.

00:01:48.100 --> 00:01:54.200
And so you have a good time, then after a
while things kind of take a

00:01:54.200 --> 00:02:00.180
hard turn, and you're a bit surprised by that,
and you, you know, try to

00:02:00.180 --> 00:02:04.230
work things out so that they can get back
to being the nice goofy person they were before.

00:02:04.230 --> 00:02:05.230
Um.

00:02:05.230 --> 00:02:06.230
&gt;&gt;Fred: so you're...

00:02:06.230 --> 00:02:07.230
&gt;&gt;Bill: It may or may not work.

00:02:07.230 --> 00:02:08.909
&gt;&gt;Fred: So you're saying this book is like
an intervention

00:02:08.909 --> 00:02:10.319
for uh, "Uncle Copyright?"

00:02:10.319 --> 00:02:11.770
&gt;&gt;Bill: Right, right, right.

00:02:11.770 --> 00:02:15.150
It's, I view
myself as being within the family.

00:02:15.150 --> 00:02:20.030
I mean, I've done it for thirty years,
so if I didn't enjoy it, it would be really

00:02:20.030 --> 00:02:21.030
a waste of time.

00:02:21.030 --> 00:02:25.120
But if you do care about something, then you
want it to work out well,

00:02:25.120 --> 00:02:29.270
and when it's not, you can either shut up,
in which case you shouldn't complain

00:02:29.270 --> 00:02:33.990
about it,um, but if you don't like the way
it's going, then you probably should say

00:02:33.990 --> 00:02:38.760
something and try to point out ways so that
your favorite aunt or uncle

00:02:38.760 --> 00:02:44.480
could be goofy again and not such a, you know,
difficult, destructive person.

00:02:44.480 --> 00:02:48.520
&gt;&gt;Fred: Well, with that then, let's start
with the, uh, the,

00:02:48.520 --> 00:02:51.630
what you view as the afflictions of copyright
or at least the ways

00:02:51.630 --> 00:02:55.060
that copyright has gone a bit off the rails
in recent years.

00:02:55.060 --> 00:03:00.660
What would, what would you say were, are sort
of your top three, uh, ills

00:03:00.660 --> 00:03:01.680
that you think need fixing?

00:03:01.680 --> 00:03:02.680
&gt;&gt;Bill: Uh huh.

00:03:02.680 --> 00:03:05.690
Right right, at least it's not the ten plagues,
with Passover

00:03:05.690 --> 00:03:06.690
coming soon.

00:03:06.690 --> 00:03:09.790
Let's see, three plagues, only three plagues,
three afflictions

00:03:09.790 --> 00:03:11.440
&gt;&gt;Fred: Frogs, boils, locusts, what are they?

00:03:11.440 --> 00:03:12.440
&gt;&gt;Bill: Right, right, right.

00:03:12.440 --> 00:03:15.480
Death of the firstborn, that's the real thing.

00:03:15.480 --> 00:03:22.209
So, one would be probably, uh, all of the
rhetoric that's used about

00:03:22.209 --> 00:03:28.569
what copyright can do, should do, is doing,
um, and sort of,

00:03:28.569 --> 00:03:33.870
the inability to get past that, the inability
to really have a rational discussion

00:03:33.870 --> 00:03:38.800
about, uh, what we want copyright to be.

00:03:38.800 --> 00:03:42.730
Maybe the second affliction
would be that, huh, all too many policy believers

00:03:42.730 --> 00:03:43.730
actually believe it.

00:03:43.730 --> 00:03:48.460
They actually believe all the things that
are said, and if you read some of the things

00:03:48.460 --> 00:03:53.450
that are said, copyrights supposedly can do
everything but cure the sick,

00:03:53.450 --> 00:03:55.890
and take care of global warming.

00:03:55.890 --> 00:04:01.520
So when something can do something like that,
um, then everyone wants to sign on.

00:04:01.520 --> 00:04:05.040
But if it can't do those things,
then people get disappointed.

00:04:05.040 --> 00:04:09.270
So it's sort of surprising that people
believe it can do all of those things.

00:04:09.270 --> 00:04:13.400
The third one might be,uh,
[takes deep breath] trade.

00:04:13.400 --> 00:04:15.640
That copyright is a trade issue, so, it's
always been

00:04:15.640 --> 00:04:17.239
a trade issue in some ways.

00:04:17.239 --> 00:04:22.680
The United States didn't protect English works
for the first hundred years, because it was

00:04:22.680 --> 00:04:28.419
our national trade policy
not to, to be able to not pay English authors.

00:04:28.419 --> 00:04:33.199
Um, but what's happened
since at least the mid-'80s, was that copyright

00:04:33.199 --> 00:04:40.360
became part of our trade agreements,
conditioning, uh, benefits for uh, providing

00:04:40.360 --> 00:04:44.830
effective and adequate protection
to U.S. works and it's become rigid.

00:04:44.830 --> 00:04:49.490
First of all, it's anti-democratic,
as the demonstrations and protests about ACTA

00:04:49.490 --> 00:04:51.629
have, uh, have pointed out.

00:04:51.629 --> 00:04:56.330
It's an anti-democratic way to make policy,
to have trade officials doing it,

00:04:56.330 --> 00:05:01.300
but once you do it, then it becomes rigid
and you can't go back,

00:05:01.300 --> 00:05:03.300
unless you abrogate the trade agreement.

00:05:03.300 --> 00:05:08.479
So let's say, like, in an ideal world,
that policy makers were data driven, like

00:05:08.479 --> 00:05:09.520
we are at Google, right?

00:05:09.520 --> 00:05:12.240
You figure out
what it is you want to do, you've got the

00:05:12.240 --> 00:05:15.479
data to support it, and then you go and do
it,

00:05:15.479 --> 00:05:20.560
and if it doesn't work, you constantly iterate
and reiterate until you get it right.

00:05:20.560 --> 00:05:24.050
That's like a logical, rational way to do
things.

00:05:24.050 --> 00:05:28.999
But once things become, uh,
put into trade agreements, you know, you don't

00:05:28.999 --> 00:05:30.669
have that flexibility any more.

00:05:30.669 --> 00:05:35.539
You either have the choice of abrogating the
trade agreement, or not.

00:05:35.539 --> 00:05:39.430
And the not part is living with things that
don't work.

00:05:39.430 --> 00:05:41.520
So, I'll give you an example.

00:05:41.520 --> 00:05:46.379
This is one that Hal Varian certainly has
provided a lot of good data on,

00:05:46.379 --> 00:05:51.419
which is, what's the appropriate length of
copyright, and back in 1998,

00:05:51.419 --> 00:05:57.189
when we extended it twenty more years, did
those twenty years lead

00:05:57.189 --> 00:06:00.180
to any more works being created?

00:06:00.180 --> 00:06:01.529
I mean, that was the argument.

00:06:01.529 --> 00:06:04.759
The argument was, well, if we extend the term
of copyright

00:06:04.759 --> 00:06:08.159
twenty more years, it's going to make people
create things

00:06:08.159 --> 00:06:09.740
that they wouldn't create.

00:06:09.740 --> 00:06:16.240
Right, that's a factual statement
and it's one that you should be able to empirically

00:06:16.240 --> 00:06:17.509
figure out.

00:06:17.509 --> 00:06:20.649
And Hal
did really great work, you know, in figuring

00:06:20.649 --> 00:06:22.580
that out.

00:06:22.580 --> 00:06:25.999
And the answer is "no",
it's not going to lead to the creation of

00:06:25.999 --> 00:06:28.259
any more works at all.

00:06:28.259 --> 00:06:29.259
And it hasn't.

00:06:29.259 --> 00:06:33.559
&gt;&gt;Fred: Right, and it always struck me, the
notion that you tell an author today

00:06:33.559 --> 00:06:40.689
that seventy years after you die, it's hard
to see that as highly motivating, uh,

00:06:40.689 --> 00:06:43.499
in the moment, even without empirical data.

00:06:43.499 --> 00:06:45.120
&gt;&gt;Bill: Right, so, so here's the fact situation.

00:06:45.120 --> 00:06:48.439
You're in 1998,
you're a policy maker, the existing term of

00:06:48.439 --> 00:06:53.580
a copyright is
your life plus 50 more years, right?

00:06:53.580 --> 00:06:57.389
And so the argument is
no, no, no, we need to incentivize people

00:06:57.389 --> 00:07:00.530
more, if you give
20 more years to copyright, then you're going

00:07:00.530 --> 00:07:03.210
to create
more works, and everyone will be happy.

00:07:03.210 --> 00:07:06.240
Well, that twenty more years,
of course, is tacked on to the end.

00:07:06.240 --> 00:07:10.479
So we're talking about somebody
say in 2012 sitting around saying, "Well,

00:07:10.479 --> 00:07:11.839
what do I do today, you know?

00:07:11.839 --> 00:07:15.750
Do I write another book, or do I take the
trash out, or find some

00:07:15.750 --> 00:07:17.169
other way to make money."

00:07:17.169 --> 00:07:21.639
Um, so in figuring out that, I think, how
long is

00:07:21.639 --> 00:07:22.689
the copyright going to last?

00:07:22.689 --> 00:07:27.050
Well, it lasts for my life, and I don't know
how long I am going to live but let's say

00:07:27.050 --> 00:07:31.559
I'm thirty and I can expect to live
to be eighty, at least.

00:07:31.559 --> 00:07:34.279
So that's fifty more years, and then you add
on fifty years

00:07:34.279 --> 00:07:35.279
after your death.

00:07:35.279 --> 00:07:36.279
That's a hundred years.

00:07:36.279 --> 00:07:38.960
And you sit around and say,
"That's actually not long enough.

00:07:38.960 --> 00:07:42.050
I'm going to do something else, you know.

00:07:42.050 --> 00:07:46.160
[laughter] Fifty more years for while I'm
alive and fifty more after I'm dead,

00:07:46.160 --> 00:07:48.139
that's just not a sufficient incentive.

00:07:48.139 --> 00:07:50.860
It's got to be seventy years
after I'm dead.

00:07:50.860 --> 00:07:53.050
It's got to be one hundred twenty years after
I'm dead."

00:07:53.050 --> 00:07:56.699
&gt;&gt;Fred: This actually, suddenly I realize
that what you said a minute ago

00:07:56.699 --> 00:08:01.209
about copyright, can cure everything except
global warming.

00:08:01.209 --> 00:08:03.379
On that time
scale maybe we need to talk about whether

00:08:03.379 --> 00:08:06.649
copyright can cure global warming,
because maybe in a hundred and fifty years-

00:08:06.649 --> 00:08:07.649
&gt;&gt;Bill: It'd be long enough,it'd be long enough.

00:08:07.649 --> 00:08:08.649
&gt;&gt;Fred: Exactly, so-

00:08:08.649 --> 00:08:09.869
&gt;&gt;Bill: But if you look at it another way,
look at it from the standpoint

00:08:09.869 --> 00:08:10.949
of a publisher, right?

00:08:10.949 --> 00:08:14.039
So the argument is, no, no, no, that's, you're
making

00:08:14.039 --> 00:08:19.949
this silly case, the real case is this, that
in 2012, a publisher is going to

00:08:19.949 --> 00:08:25.870
give you more money, right, for that work,
based upon it lasting seventy years

00:08:25.870 --> 00:08:29.889
after you're dead rather than fifty, because
you don't know when you're

00:08:29.889 --> 00:08:34.919
going to die, but your publisher will, allegedly,
live forever, so right now

00:08:34.919 --> 00:08:38.490
the present value is going to be more because
we're going to give you more.

00:08:38.490 --> 00:08:42.180
But, but that's not true either, if you talk
to publishers, no publisher

00:08:42.180 --> 00:08:47.620
is going to give you more money today based
upon, allegedly, twenty more years,

00:08:47.620 --> 00:08:48.620
you know a hundred years.

00:08:48.620 --> 00:08:50.330
Because we're talking about the difference
between

00:08:50.330 --> 00:08:53.810
a hundred year copyright and a hundred and
twenty year copyright.

00:08:53.810 --> 00:08:58.530
And most works don't have any market, and
if they have a market,

00:08:58.530 --> 00:09:02.340
it's not more than a year, two years, three
years, in my case,

00:09:02.340 --> 00:09:04.090
you know, a few weeks.

00:09:04.090 --> 00:09:05.090
[laughter]
but..

00:09:05.090 --> 00:09:06.090
&gt;&gt;Fred:Buy it now.

00:09:06.090 --> 00:09:07.090
Buy it now

00:09:07.090 --> 00:09:08.090
&gt;&gt;Bill: The publishers don't give me more--.

00:09:08.090 --> 00:09:09.090
Buy it now, right.

00:09:09.090 --> 00:09:12.560
&gt;&gt; Fred: This brings me back to the first
two ailments you mentioned,

00:09:12.560 --> 00:09:18.890
uh, of copyright, mainly what you view as
somewhat unrealistic rhetoric,

00:09:18.890 --> 00:09:21.800
and the fact that policymakers seem to accept
it.

00:09:21.800 --> 00:09:25.410
And I'm curious, one of the main themes in
your book that you really decry

00:09:25.410 --> 00:09:26.780
is this notion.

00:09:26.780 --> 00:09:30.220
Which really is, you know, often, you hear
it often at the heart

00:09:30.220 --> 00:09:33.150
of the debates about copyright, is this notion
that copyright law

00:09:33.150 --> 00:09:36.270
is necessary to create an incentive for creativity.

00:09:36.270 --> 00:09:41.430
I mean that
really is a central story that copyright supporters

00:09:41.430 --> 00:09:45.560
tell,
and you really take, take that notion to task.

00:09:45.560 --> 00:09:49.490
What's your sense
of why that's actually overselling what copyright

00:09:49.490 --> 00:09:50.490
can actually deliver?

00:09:50.490 --> 00:09:54.630
&gt;&gt;Bill: Right, so if I could go back to your
sports metaphor about, you know,

00:09:54.630 --> 00:09:58.480
liking a sports team, whether it's the 49ers,
and I grew up in Marin,

00:09:58.480 --> 00:10:01.690
so while I live in Connecticut, I'm still
a 49ers fan.

00:10:01.690 --> 00:10:04.730
You know when
you interview the losing coach, usually they

00:10:04.730 --> 00:10:08.430
say something like,
"You know, we’re going to get back to basics.

00:10:08.430 --> 00:10:12.280
Learning the ball, throwing the ball, good
defense."

00:10:12.280 --> 00:10:14.680
And I always think, well, aren't you supposed
to be doing that anyway?

00:10:14.680 --> 00:10:17.040
[laughter] I mean, why is that going to be
something new,

00:10:17.040 --> 00:10:19.270
that you're going to get back to the basics?

00:10:19.270 --> 00:10:22.550
So if you're going to apply that
to copyright, what are the basics?

00:10:22.550 --> 00:10:24.760
What do we actually want it to do?

00:10:24.760 --> 00:10:28.310
And I don't think that law is an end to itself.

00:10:28.310 --> 00:10:30.990
The goal is not to have laws.

00:10:30.990 --> 00:10:33.170
&gt;&gt;Fred: Don't tell politicians.

00:10:33.170 --> 00:10:34.170
&gt;&gt;Bill: Yeah, yeah.

00:10:34.170 --> 00:10:40.630
Well, when I went to work for Congress,
my father, who, uh, lives in Sonoma, but who's

00:10:40.630 --> 00:10:44.040
really
a politically really conservative guy, was

00:10:44.040 --> 00:10:48.570
deeply disappointed in me,
because he thought I was going to work for

00:10:48.570 --> 00:10:55.990
an, you know, organization
that didn't do upstanding good things, and

00:10:55.990 --> 00:10:58.960
passed too many laws,
and that they were there just to pass laws

00:10:58.960 --> 00:10:59.960
you know.

00:10:59.960 --> 00:11:00.960
That was their product.

00:11:00.960 --> 00:11:02.110
Their product was passing laws.

00:11:02.110 --> 00:11:07.230
So he said, "Look, if you're going to do any
of this copyright stuff, then any new law

00:11:07.230 --> 00:11:10.000
you gotta
make sure that you repeal three others.

00:11:10.000 --> 00:11:12.940
[laughter] Otherwise,
you know, don't do it.

00:11:12.940 --> 00:11:14.990
Don't, don't give us more laws."

00:11:14.990 --> 00:11:18.680
So, if you take that approach, that law is
actually

00:11:18.680 --> 00:11:24.710
a tool and not an end to itself, it's a tool
to do things, hopefully, that only law can

00:11:24.710 --> 00:11:25.710
do.

00:11:25.710 --> 00:11:28.690
Um, I don't think we want laws to do things
that laws

00:11:28.690 --> 00:11:29.780
aren't supposed to do.

00:11:29.780 --> 00:11:34.720
Things that are business problems, right,the
solutions to business problems are business

00:11:34.720 --> 00:11:35.720
problems.

00:11:35.720 --> 00:11:37.750
[chuckles] .
I mean, if you have a business problem, the

00:11:37.750 --> 00:11:41.680
way to handle that
is to have a better business model, and not

00:11:41.680 --> 00:11:46.970
to have a law
that supports a bad business model.

00:11:46.970 --> 00:11:51.580
So if you look at one of the basics
of copyright, you know the learning, throwing,

00:11:51.580 --> 00:11:54.870
a good defense, right,
what's that supposed to be for copyright?

00:11:54.870 --> 00:11:59.530
And so people say lots of things.

00:11:59.530 --> 00:12:03.430
One of the embarrassing things
is that no one can actually agree what copyright

00:12:03.430 --> 00:12:04.430
is supposed to do.

00:12:04.430 --> 00:12:08.750
Um, and that makes rational policy making
pretty difficult when no one can

00:12:08.750 --> 00:12:10.470
agree what it's supposed to do.

00:12:10.470 --> 00:12:14.960
So if you want to have data driven,
rational driven copyright law, it would be

00:12:14.960 --> 00:12:19.030
nice for everyone to agree
on what it's supposed to do, right?

00:12:19.030 --> 00:12:22.610
Because you can't empirically test that,
you can't figure out whether it works if you

00:12:22.610 --> 00:12:24.440
can't agree about what it's supposed to do.

00:12:24.440 --> 00:12:29.030
So, some of the things people say it's supposed
to do, is to prevent

00:12:29.030 --> 00:12:30.920
free riding.

00:12:30.920 --> 00:12:33.880
That actually makes sense, I actually think
it can do that.

00:12:33.880 --> 00:12:37.540
If you have a motion picture that cost two
hundred million dollars to produce,

00:12:37.540 --> 00:12:41.830
and someone else comes along and captures
all the investment on that,

00:12:41.830 --> 00:12:44.220
that's something copyright could actually
do.

00:12:44.220 --> 00:12:45.520
That's a negative thing, though.

00:12:45.520 --> 00:12:47.190
That's actually stopping something.

00:12:47.190 --> 00:12:51.270
Now, the positive things
it's supposed to do are a little more difficult,

00:12:51.270 --> 00:12:52.270
I think, to establish.

00:12:52.270 --> 00:12:55.580
One of which is to encourage creativity, right?

00:12:55.580 --> 00:13:01.090
So you say, the purpose of copyright
is to encourage creativity and we need creativity

00:13:01.090 --> 00:13:06.080
because creativity
is necessary for culture, and therefore copyright

00:13:06.080 --> 00:13:07.480
is necessary for culture.

00:13:07.480 --> 00:13:11.690
This is like a syllogism, uh, for that, and
so we all want culture,

00:13:11.690 --> 00:13:15.060
therefore we all want creativity, and we need
copyright for that,

00:13:15.060 --> 00:13:19.220
because without copyright, we won't have creativity
or culture.

00:13:19.220 --> 00:13:23.550
But, I'm, if you break down the syllogism,
I'm not really sure it's true.

00:13:23.550 --> 00:13:30.890
I'm not actually sure that copyright causes
more creative works

00:13:30.890 --> 00:13:32.960
to be created than otherwise would, right?

00:13:32.960 --> 00:13:34.810
This is a "but for" argument, right?

00:13:34.810 --> 00:13:39.430
But for copyright,
people wouldn't create creative things.

00:13:39.430 --> 00:13:43.020
This is leaving aside
the free riding argument, which is a different

00:13:43.020 --> 00:13:44.020
one.

00:13:44.020 --> 00:13:46.941
And so,
I don't know, I don't know that the end, this

00:13:46.941 --> 00:13:49.770
is a question,
I don't have an answer, it's just a question.

00:13:49.770 --> 00:13:54.020
I don't know that when people are creating
things that they say

00:13:54.020 --> 00:13:57.240
"well, my goal is to own a copyright."

00:13:57.240 --> 00:13:58.420
I doubt that.

00:13:58.420 --> 00:14:03.100
I don't, I certainly think it's not true
that as consumers, we really care.

00:14:03.100 --> 00:14:09.030
Now, I'm an avaricious consumer, of cultural
works.

00:14:09.030 --> 00:14:13.420
I buy thousands of
dollars of sheet music and books, hard copy

00:14:13.420 --> 00:14:14.420
books.

00:14:14.420 --> 00:14:17.950
I have ten year old twins who, you know, read
a lot, too.

00:14:17.950 --> 00:14:21.800
But I've never bought anything, or not bought
anything,

00:14:21.800 --> 00:14:23.910
because it was under copyright and in the
public domain.

00:14:23.910 --> 00:14:25.920
I really don't care.

00:14:25.920 --> 00:14:29.340
It doesn't mean I don't care
about people getting paid, I do, but that's

00:14:29.340 --> 00:14:30.480
a different question.

00:14:30.480 --> 00:14:34.460
I buy things because it has value for me,
and part of the value

00:14:34.460 --> 00:14:36.220
is not whether it's under copyright.

00:14:36.220 --> 00:14:40.330
And I think that people
create things, not because they want to own

00:14:40.330 --> 00:14:43.661
a copyright,
but because they want to create it, they want

00:14:43.661 --> 00:14:46.810
to make money,
they want to distribute their ideas, they

00:14:46.810 --> 00:14:50.110
want to engage
in intellectual discussion with people.

00:14:50.110 --> 00:14:53.730
Um, so I'm not sure that giving people longer
term copyright,

00:14:53.730 --> 00:14:57.830
or stronger rights, is going to actually incentivize
people

00:14:57.830 --> 00:15:00.130
to do things that they wouldn't.

00:15:00.130 --> 00:15:03.940
Um, it's certainly not true that copyright
historically

00:15:03.940 --> 00:15:05.960
has led to more diverse works.

00:15:05.960 --> 00:15:10.360
I mean, historically,
work that's sort of based on artificial scarcity,

00:15:10.360 --> 00:15:15.050
and gatekeepers and the rule of copyright,
at least in the analog world,

00:15:15.050 --> 00:15:20.600
was to make sure that those gatekeepers could
control the distribution

00:15:20.600 --> 00:15:24.670
of physical copies and limit the number of
works and the prices that were,

00:15:24.670 --> 00:15:26.340
that were out there.

00:15:26.340 --> 00:15:30.270
So I'm not sure it's demonstratively true
that it leads to creativity,

00:15:30.270 --> 00:15:31.950
but it's an important question to ask.

00:15:31.950 --> 00:15:36.170
It's an important thing
to figure out why people do stuff, um, so--

00:15:36.170 --> 00:15:39.540
&gt;&gt;Fred: As I was reading the book, on that
point, I was really struck

00:15:39.540 --> 00:15:44.100
by the notion that there's really two intended
beneficiaries here,

00:15:44.100 --> 00:15:46.040
that may not actually be related.

00:15:46.040 --> 00:15:48.990
So, on the one hand,you have
the free riding question you mentioned.

00:15:48.990 --> 00:15:52.230
I often talk
to movie executives who say, "well, it may

00:15:52.230 --> 00:15:56.460
be really cheap
to go and record your own music nowadays,

00:15:56.460 --> 00:15:59.780
or it might be
really cheap for you to write your own blog,

00:15:59.780 --> 00:16:04.490
but it's not cheap
to create the kind of special effects extravaganzas

00:16:04.490 --> 00:16:08.220
that draw people
into the theaters for the new Transformers

00:16:08.220 --> 00:16:10.000
installment or what have you."

00:16:10.000 --> 00:16:11.000
&gt;&gt;Bill: Hangover, part three.

00:16:11.000 --> 00:16:12.000
&gt;&gt;Fred: Right.

00:16:12.000 --> 00:16:18.470
So the question is, I really wondered,
are we asking too much of copyright to serve

00:16:18.470 --> 00:16:22.160
these two very different needs and communities?

00:16:22.160 --> 00:16:26.279
I mean,
we need one thing for people to recoup these

00:16:26.279 --> 00:16:30.670
three hundred million dollar investments,
that require thousands of people to work together

00:16:30.670 --> 00:16:34.940
in a coordinated way
to launch a movie, but then we also want copyright

00:16:34.940 --> 00:16:40.780
to encourage, create incentives
for individual creators to write that next

00:16:40.780 --> 00:16:44.940
song, or write that next book,
or write that next blog post.

00:16:44.940 --> 00:16:48.120
Is it your sense that we ought to somehow
have

00:16:48.120 --> 00:16:51.780
two different systems, or do you think it's
compatible to have copyright

00:16:51.780 --> 00:16:52.780
handle both sides?

00:16:52.780 --> 00:16:53.780
&gt;&gt;Bill: Right.

00:16:53.780 --> 00:16:56.090
So I think that there's two different problems
here,

00:16:56.090 --> 00:16:58.080
one of which is using the word creativity.

00:16:58.080 --> 00:17:01.750
So, when we talk about
creativity here, I think we're talking about

00:17:01.750 --> 00:17:03.570
it in the colloquial sense.

00:17:03.570 --> 00:17:09.880
We're talking about works that are interesting,
works that have some sort

00:17:09.880 --> 00:17:13.589
of appeal, aesthetic appeal, emotional appeal,
something like that.

00:17:13.589 --> 00:17:16.589
But that's not the sense that copyright uses
the word creativity.

00:17:16.589 --> 00:17:22.169
So, one of the big things, one of the big
problems, the ailments as you said,

00:17:22.169 --> 00:17:27.530
is that when policymakers talk about encouraging
creativity through copyright law,

00:17:27.530 --> 00:17:31.990
copyright law uses creativity in a totally
different way.

00:17:31.990 --> 00:17:36.070
Creativity in copyright means
only that you didn't copy it from somebody

00:17:36.070 --> 00:17:41.600
else and there's like a tiny bit
of something that somebody else , you know,

00:17:41.600 --> 00:17:43.690
didn't do, or didn't do in the same way.

00:17:43.690 --> 00:17:48.740
And the reason for that is, we don't want
judges to be arbiters of what's art.

00:17:48.740 --> 00:17:54.350
We don't want judges to decide subjectively,
"this is a creative work, and this isn’t."

00:17:54.350 --> 00:17:59.690
And so, from within the system of copyright,
that actually makes a lot of sense,

00:17:59.690 --> 00:18:03.581
but when you use the same word in a colloquial
sense and say you want

00:18:03.581 --> 00:18:08.889
to encourage creativity, through copyright
law, you're using a totally different word

00:18:08.889 --> 00:18:09.889
to mean different things.

00:18:09.889 --> 00:18:15.190
So under copyright, we protect emails, perhaps
Twitter postings,

00:18:15.190 --> 00:18:19.830
protect business documents, lawyers' cease
and desist letters, we protect virtually anything

00:18:19.830 --> 00:18:24.110
that anyone creates, and we do it without
any formalities.

00:18:24.110 --> 00:18:28.850
So to say copyright law
encourages creativity sort of misses the point

00:18:28.850 --> 00:18:34.149
that most works that are protected
under copyright are not works that are creative

00:18:34.149 --> 00:18:37.669
in the colloquial sense that we're debating.

00:18:37.669 --> 00:18:40.230
It's like using, well, I'll give you a great
example.

00:18:40.230 --> 00:18:42.270
&gt;&gt;Fred: You, you haven't been reading my emails,
Bill.

00:18:42.270 --> 00:18:43.270
[laughter]

00:18:43.270 --> 00:18:44.270
Very, very creative.

00:18:44.270 --> 00:18:45.270
&gt;&gt;Bill: All right.

00:18:45.270 --> 00:18:47.929
[chuckles] So in 1990, I was still working
for Congress,

00:18:47.929 --> 00:18:52.330
and we wanted to protect architectural works,
the three dimensional buildings,

00:18:52.330 --> 00:18:55.440
not plans or drawings because they were already
protected and we wanted to do it

00:18:55.440 --> 00:18:57.600
because we had a treaty obligation to do it.

00:18:57.600 --> 00:19:02.090
You still had to make the case though,
to members of Congress why you should do that.

00:19:02.090 --> 00:19:06.750
So I organized hearings, and I had
Michael Graves, who was a very famous architect

00:19:06.750 --> 00:19:09.080
at the time,
we had the Frank Lloyd Wright estate, we had

00:19:09.080 --> 00:19:14.509
a number of famous architects
come and explain why their works are creative,

00:19:14.509 --> 00:19:15.509
right.

00:19:15.509 --> 00:19:17.119
And you could get that.

00:19:17.119 --> 00:19:20.700
That was easy to see why they
re artists just like everybody else.

00:19:20.700 --> 00:19:25.629
The truth of the matter was, that most architectural
copyright infringement actions

00:19:25.629 --> 00:19:32.509
are over semi-custom or far, far lower works.

00:19:32.509 --> 00:19:37.950
So, you know, it was
a, you know, I don't know how to describe

00:19:37.950 --> 00:19:38.950
it.

00:19:38.950 --> 00:19:44.450
[laughs] It was use of creativity
through famous architects to make a case why

00:19:44.450 --> 00:19:48.690
we should do a general law
that applied to other works.

00:19:48.690 --> 00:19:54.039
And that's one of the problems with using
creativity in copyright as sort of a rallying

00:19:54.039 --> 00:19:58.529
cry, or as it can do something
is that you are using one case, that may be

00:19:58.529 --> 00:20:02.210
easy to prove, for ninety-nine percent of
the cases

00:20:02.210 --> 00:20:05.489
that have very different policy issues.

00:20:05.489 --> 00:20:12.600
The second problem is that the scope of copyright,
the incentives that you would need for a 300

00:20:12.600 --> 00:20:16.840
thousand dollar movie
are, uh, are they do fine in the market place.

00:20:16.840 --> 00:20:22.279
The stuff that we say that we want
are works that don't do well in the market

00:20:22.279 --> 00:20:23.279
place.

00:20:23.279 --> 00:20:26.999
And so, the problem saying
that copyright is going to solve everything

00:20:26.999 --> 00:20:31.809
is that it may solve free riding problems
for the expensive works, and should, but it

00:20:31.809 --> 00:20:36.520
doesn't do anything for the ninety-nine percent,
right?

00:20:36.520 --> 00:20:42.169
Personally, um, we would be better taking
the hundreds of millions of dollars we use

00:20:42.169 --> 00:20:46.590
for enforcement,
and going to East Palo Alto and having something

00:20:46.590 --> 00:20:49.629
like they have in Venezuela, El Sistema.

00:20:49.629 --> 00:20:54.389
If we really want to encourage creativity
among masses of people, other people, let's

00:20:54.389 --> 00:20:57.710
spend money to do it, because that's the only
way it's going to happen.

00:20:57.710 --> 00:21:03.010
And if we don't do that, if we claim "don't
worry , we're going to give you a copyright",

00:21:03.010 --> 00:21:04.010
that's baloney.

00:21:04.010 --> 00:21:05.010
&gt;&gt;Fred:mmm

00:21:05.010 --> 00:21:08.671
&gt;&gt;Bill: I mean, I play bass clarinet, and
I'm trying to encourage more people

00:21:08.671 --> 00:21:11.580
to write more works for bass clarinet.

00:21:11.580 --> 00:21:14.090
So if I go to them and say,
"Hey, guess what?

00:21:14.090 --> 00:21:18.410
If you spend six months or a year writing
a new piece for bass clarinet,

00:21:18.410 --> 00:21:21.259
at the end of that time, you're going to have
a copyright."

00:21:21.259 --> 00:21:23.149
No, I, … they'll laugh at me.

00:21:23.149 --> 00:21:26.860
There are other reasons for them to do it,
and copyright isn't one of them.

00:21:26.860 --> 00:21:32.039
So if we want diverse cultural works, we have
to figure out ways outside of copyright to

00:21:32.039 --> 00:21:33.039
do it.

00:21:33.039 --> 00:21:35.390
It's not that it's a knock on copyright, it
isn't.

00:21:35.390 --> 00:21:38.970
It's that it can do some things,
but there's other things it can't do.

00:21:38.970 --> 00:21:43.249
And so if we fool ourselves into thinking
it can do everything,

00:21:43.249 --> 00:21:44.770
then it's just not.

00:21:44.770 --> 00:21:45.770
It can't.

00:21:45.770 --> 00:21:50.039
&gt;&gt;Fred: Alright, so your discussion about
extending copyrights to three dimensional

00:21:50.039 --> 00:21:53.019
works of architecture
reminds me that of, a lot of the discussion

00:21:53.019 --> 00:21:57.299
in your book reflects a disappointment, if
you will,

00:21:57.299 --> 00:22:03.789
in policy makers who have not demanded empirical,
factual support for expansions of copyright,

00:22:03.789 --> 00:22:08.570
who have not been more, I guess, discerning
customers when it comes to proposals.

00:22:08.570 --> 00:22:13.419
Um, in fact, you used
a term in the book which I quite liked, you

00:22:13.419 --> 00:22:14.769
called it "lobbynomics."

00:22:14.769 --> 00:22:20.049
That rather than economics,
policy makers, too often, are swayed by "lobbynomics",

00:22:20.049 --> 00:22:22.419
by whatever the lobbyists come in and deliver.

00:22:22.419 --> 00:22:27.470
Um, so I guess as I was reading that, the
question came to me, do you feel like fixing

00:22:27.470 --> 00:22:30.169
many
of many of the problems in copyright require

00:22:30.169 --> 00:22:34.869
us to first fix a larger flaw
in the political process?

00:22:34.869 --> 00:22:38.039
And, if so, that's a pretty tall order.

00:22:38.039 --> 00:22:40.779
Or do you think
that there's actually hope to make progress

00:22:40.779 --> 00:22:46.559
on copyright without fixing what
is viewed by a lot of people as a larger difficulty

00:22:46.559 --> 00:22:51.919
with communicating
empirical, fact driven analysis to Congress?

00:22:51.919 --> 00:22:57.970
&gt;&gt;Bill: Yeah, so I worked on Capitol Hill
for seven years, and I have, you know, some

00:22:57.970 --> 00:23:04.650
experience,
with how members of Congress listen to issues,

00:23:04.650 --> 00:23:07.759
and who they listen to and you know, things
have changed

00:23:07.759 --> 00:23:09.190
over time.

00:23:09.190 --> 00:23:16.220
But once, when I was working for the copyright
office, this was in 1989, I was on this panel

00:23:16.220 --> 00:23:19.700
in San Francisco with John Perry Barlow, one
of your friends.

00:23:19.700 --> 00:23:26.549
And it was, you know, it was 1989,
and there were a bunch of programmers who

00:23:26.549 --> 00:23:29.700
were very upset about software copyright.

00:23:29.700 --> 00:23:33.100
They thought
it was inappropriate, and I actually agree

00:23:33.100 --> 00:23:38.190
with them, but it was an inappropriate thing
and they wanted me,

00:23:38.190 --> 00:23:42.049
as a member of the government, to go fix it
for them.

00:23:42.049 --> 00:23:48.799
And I said," You know, unless
you get off your butt", I think I used a different

00:23:48.799 --> 00:23:52.220
word,
"and do something about it yourself, no, it's

00:23:52.220 --> 00:23:54.289
not going to change."

00:23:54.289 --> 00:24:02.370
I grew up in Marin, and I was a child in the
'60s in Marin, and in

00:24:02.370 --> 00:24:05.950
those days, there were actual protests about
stuff.

00:24:05.950 --> 00:24:12.340
I remember I went to the People's,
the second People's Park March, this was in

00:24:12.340 --> 00:24:13.489
May of 1969.

00:24:13.489 --> 00:24:19.710
There was the first one in which Ed Meese,
this was when Reagan was governor,

00:24:19.710 --> 00:24:24.590
we had him for eight years, eight or sixteen
years.

00:24:24.590 --> 00:24:26.980
[chuckles]
He was governor for eight years, then President

00:24:26.980 --> 00:24:27.980
for eight
years.

00:24:27.980 --> 00:24:32.090
Ed Meese took over the police in, in Berkeley
and

00:24:32.090 --> 00:24:35.789
and there was disputes about People's Park,
and he took over the police

00:24:35.789 --> 00:24:40.210
and during the protest, the police shot at
people, and one guy was killed,

00:24:40.210 --> 00:24:45.159
another guy was blinded, and then two weeks
later there was a protest.

00:24:45.159 --> 00:24:50.809
A lot of people came, I came, you go over
to the East Shore Freeway,

00:24:50.809 --> 00:24:53.850
it's called the Bayshore Freeway, the whole
thing, I used to call it the East Shore,

00:24:53.850 --> 00:24:57.419
but you go along that and you get on University
Avenue,

00:24:57.419 --> 00:25:01.539
and there's like that little cloverleaf there
and like right on top of the cloverleaf

00:25:01.539 --> 00:25:04.929
there was a big tank, because Reagan had called
out,

00:25:04.929 --> 00:25:07.460
like 2700 or so National Guardsmen.

00:25:07.460 --> 00:25:11.289
And all along the way
there were these guns, and bayonets, like

00:25:11.289 --> 00:25:12.529
inches away from you and stuff.

00:25:12.529 --> 00:25:17.009
And you just prayed no one did anything really
stupid, and they didn't,

00:25:17.009 --> 00:25:22.619
but people did, did complain.

00:25:22.619 --> 00:25:24.869
Whether people listened or not, I know Johnson
didn't

00:25:24.869 --> 00:25:25.869
run again.

00:25:25.869 --> 00:25:30.039
But in 1989, people then said to me, "Well,
you know, you work in Washington,

00:25:30.039 --> 00:25:33.110
you're a government official, go fix it."

00:25:33.110 --> 00:25:37.299
I said, "That's not the way this system works,
if you really don't like something, you've

00:25:37.299 --> 00:25:38.640
got to do it yourself.

00:25:38.640 --> 00:25:42.620
You have to make
your voice heard and only then will things

00:25:42.620 --> 00:25:43.620
change."

00:25:43.620 --> 00:25:44.620
&gt;&gt;Fred: So do you think-

00:25:44.620 --> 00:25:45.620
&gt;&gt;Bill: It took twenty-three years,[laughs]

00:25:45.620 --> 00:25:48.730
&gt;&gt;Fred: Do you think the most recent events
are a part of something like that?

00:25:48.730 --> 00:25:52.739
&gt;&gt;Bill: That was too easy a transition for
you.[laughter] Yeah, yeah, it

00:25:52.739 --> 00:25:56.220
took twenty-three years, and things did change.

00:25:56.220 --> 00:26:01.521
So, I guess the point of my story is
that if you want things to change, then you

00:26:01.521 --> 00:26:02.521
have to do it yourself.

00:26:02.521 --> 00:26:06.110
&gt;&gt; Fred: You know as they used to say on the
radio, if you don't like the news, make some

00:26:06.110 --> 00:26:07.110
of your own.

00:26:07.110 --> 00:26:08.110
&gt;&gt; Bill: Yeah.

00:26:08.110 --> 00:26:11.840
&gt;&gt; Fred: So before we open to questions, I
want shift from the the negative side of this,

00:26:11.840 --> 00:26:14.940
there's
a lot in this book that you view as copyright's

00:26:14.940 --> 00:26:19.789
failings, uh to some
of the sort of positive, uh, prescriptions,

00:26:19.789 --> 00:26:22.690
if you will,
for how you think things could be made better.

00:26:22.690 --> 00:26:27.369
One of the things I noticed in particular
your emphasis on shifting

00:26:27.369 --> 00:26:31.269
from an analysis of exclusive rights, this
idea that copyright owners

00:26:31.269 --> 00:26:34.549
should be the only one who should be allowed
to make copies,

00:26:34.549 --> 00:26:39.019
or distribute the work, or publicly perform
it, to a system that focuses

00:26:39.019 --> 00:26:41.269
more on remuneration.

00:26:41.269 --> 00:26:44.330
Making sure that rights holders, and I guess
by extension,

00:26:44.330 --> 00:26:49.590
creators themselves, are paid for what they
do even if they don't have exclusive control.

00:26:49.590 --> 00:26:50.590
&gt;&gt; Bill: Mmm hmm.

00:26:50.590 --> 00:26:53.759
&gt;&gt;Fred: I wonder, I mean, that’s, in some
ways, that's a real departure

00:26:53.759 --> 00:26:55.230
from traditional copyrights.

00:26:55.230 --> 00:27:00.470
Certainly, for the past hundred odd years,
formally, it has been about exclusive rights.

00:27:00.470 --> 00:27:04.970
Umm, what do you say to creators
who say, "I would rather have the right to

00:27:04.970 --> 00:27:10.549
say no, than the right to get paid
a few nickels and not have the right to say

00:27:10.549 --> 00:27:11.549
no?"

00:27:11.549 --> 00:27:15.049
&gt;&gt;Bill: Right, the short answer is, you can't
eat ideology.

00:27:15.049 --> 00:27:19.789
The longer answer is that
I don't, I don't regard the book as saying

00:27:19.789 --> 00:27:20.789
copyrights failed.

00:27:20.789 --> 00:27:22.179
That's sort of an anthropomorphic thing.

00:27:22.179 --> 00:27:26.179
I mean a law isn't a thing, you know, it doesn't
have feelings,

00:27:26.179 --> 00:27:28.210
can't hurt its feelings.

00:27:28.210 --> 00:27:31.690
I don't think you can respect it in the sense
that you

00:27:31.690 --> 00:27:32.690
can respect people.

00:27:32.690 --> 00:27:34.850
It either works well, or it doesn't.

00:27:34.850 --> 00:27:39.480
And it will work well
if it does the things it's supposed to do,

00:27:39.480 --> 00:27:41.799
if it's fit for its purpose.

00:27:41.799 --> 00:27:46.320
And if it doesn't, then it's not working well,
and you need to change it.

00:27:46.320 --> 00:27:50.889
It's that simple, so it's not a sense of disappointment,
you know, you let me down,

00:27:50.889 --> 00:27:54.580
it's more like the coach thing, you know,
"we're going to get back to basics: throwing,

00:27:54.580 --> 00:27:55.580
running,
good defense, you know."

00:27:55.580 --> 00:27:59.419
We got to get back to, my point is, getting
people paid, right?

00:27:59.419 --> 00:28:04.649
If you want to encourage creativity, if you
want to have more works, I think a good way

00:28:04.649 --> 00:28:07.529
to do that is to make sure people get paid.

00:28:07.529 --> 00:28:13.629
So, in the past, the sort of model,
the conceptual model has been that control

00:28:13.629 --> 00:28:15.179
equals payment.

00:28:15.179 --> 00:28:18.919
That if I create something,
the only way I am going to get paid is if

00:28:18.919 --> 00:28:22.190
I can control most things about it.

00:28:22.190 --> 00:28:27.869
I mean, the ideal in the golden age of cinema,
of movies, was of course complete control.

00:28:27.869 --> 00:28:32.830
You own the writers, you own the stars, you
own copyright and the movie, you own

00:28:32.830 --> 00:28:35.859
the theaters, you own everything vertically.

00:28:35.859 --> 00:28:39.749
Now, that was a great system, and
Jack Valenti once gave this speech in which

00:28:39.749 --> 00:28:44.429
he bemoaned the Department of Justice
killing that system of control.

00:28:44.429 --> 00:28:49.230
But that was the model, the model was
control equals payment, and copyright is what

00:28:49.230 --> 00:28:50.870
gave you control.

00:28:50.870 --> 00:28:54.090
so, copyright equals control equals money.

00:28:54.090 --> 00:28:56.320
In the end,
it was still about money, right?

00:28:56.320 --> 00:29:00.250
But the thought was that the only way
to get the money was to control it and the

00:29:00.250 --> 00:29:03.409
only way to control it was through copyright.

00:29:03.409 --> 00:29:05.640
That was the system.

00:29:05.640 --> 00:29:11.179
It worked well, not well, good sometimes,
not other times, depending upon on well

00:29:11.179 --> 00:29:14.249
it matched business models and consumer demand.

00:29:14.249 --> 00:29:18.830
I mean, the one thing that copyright
can never do is to make people buy the stuff

00:29:18.830 --> 00:29:19.830
they don't want.

00:29:19.830 --> 00:29:24.600
You know, if you take it as a coercive thing,
sure, maybe it can stop people from doing

00:29:24.600 --> 00:29:28.600
things, but I think if you want to make money,
your approach has to be different.

00:29:28.600 --> 00:29:31.419
You have to give people things that they want.

00:29:31.419 --> 00:29:35.389
You want to make them do things,
you want to make them buy stuff, and copyright

00:29:35.389 --> 00:29:36.389
can't do that.

00:29:36.389 --> 00:29:39.970
Whatever else it can do,
I am a hundred percent convinced that it cannot

00:29:39.970 --> 00:29:42.749
make people buy things they don't want to
buy.

00:29:42.749 --> 00:29:47.409
And that really should be the focus, if the
goal, to go back to the coach thing, if the

00:29:47.409 --> 00:29:49.249
goal is
to get people paid.

00:29:49.249 --> 00:29:56.820
Now in the past, having an analog world, having
artificial scarcity, and having copyright

00:29:56.820 --> 00:30:00.450
could get you a lot of that, but that's just
not true anymore.

00:30:00.450 --> 00:30:04.049
You know it's not true, you can't,
you have a digital environment, you have digital

00:30:04.049 --> 00:30:06.779
abundance and you can't control it.

00:30:06.779 --> 00:30:14.399
So the idea that you're going to graft some
eighteenth, seventeenth century form of control

00:30:14.399 --> 00:30:19.710
onto a system that you don't have control
just really doesn't make sense to me.

00:30:19.710 --> 00:30:24.559
So what you need to do is figure out a way
for people to get paid, 'cause that's the

00:30:24.559 --> 00:30:25.559
object.

00:30:25.559 --> 00:30:27.440
And it's good,
it's proper that people should get paid for

00:30:27.440 --> 00:30:28.909
things that they create.

00:30:28.909 --> 00:30:31.779
The goal we should share, the question
is how you do it.

00:30:31.779 --> 00:30:35.090
And so what I think you have to do is give
up that idea

00:30:35.090 --> 00:30:37.090
that copyright equals control.

00:30:37.090 --> 00:30:39.640
Umm, because it's not there.

00:30:39.640 --> 00:30:44.929
Why invest so many resources
in something you can't do anyway?

00:30:44.929 --> 00:30:46.600
And do something else, and that something
else

00:30:46.600 --> 00:30:51.960
is either abandon exclusive rights, for most
things, not for everything.

00:30:51.960 --> 00:30:56.609
If I write a novel, and a motion picture company
wants to make a motion picture out of it,

00:30:56.609 --> 00:30:57.609
then yeah.

00:30:57.609 --> 00:30:59.109
Those sort of one to one things you can still
do.

00:30:59.109 --> 00:31:02.950
But I think what people are most upset about
is not those one to one things, because those

00:31:02.950 --> 00:31:04.429
one to one things still work.

00:31:04.429 --> 00:31:05.820
It's the other stuff.

00:31:05.820 --> 00:31:09.789
So the other stuff has to be handled differently,
either through compulsory licenses,

00:31:09.789 --> 00:31:16.580
through tariffs, through collective administration
of rights, through Creative Commons licenses,

00:31:16.580 --> 00:31:17.580
whatever else.

00:31:17.580 --> 00:31:23.090
So I think we actually do have to shift from
a rule, from a model of control

00:31:23.090 --> 00:31:25.950
to a model of payment instead.

00:31:25.950 --> 00:31:29.429
So if you really want to say, "I really care
about my ideology,

00:31:29.429 --> 00:31:35.259
it's mine and you can't use it," that was
nice, but I don't think it actually works

00:31:35.259 --> 00:31:37.909
anymore,
and so you can't take that to the bank.

00:31:37.909 --> 00:31:40.760
And I'd rather you can take something to the
bank instead.

