00:33:49.789 --> 00:33:56.220
How to do that, I agree with your
approach, and that's this: we had, in the

00:33:56.220 --> 00:34:01.350
United States, until either 1978 for most
works,

00:34:01.350 --> 00:34:08.810
or 1992 for others, a system that actually
was amazingly great

00:34:08.810 --> 00:34:12.260
at giving market signals for the worth of
things.

00:34:12.260 --> 00:34:17.090
So if you want to approach this question empirically,
in a data driven way,

00:34:17.090 --> 00:34:23.650
you would try to figure out
how long does the market itself say the commercial

00:34:23.650 --> 00:34:27.020
value of a work is, right?

00:34:27.020 --> 00:34:28.840
And there's lots
of different ways you can do this.

00:34:28.840 --> 00:34:30.612
You can look at certain books
in print, you can look and see

00:34:30.612 --> 00:34:33.240
how long certain books are in print.

00:34:33.240 --> 00:34:37.470
Or you can do what the gentleman was suggesting,
is look at formalities.

00:34:37.470 --> 00:34:43.060
So, in the United States,
we had a system where you had variously, say,

00:34:43.060 --> 00:34:49.620
an original twenty-eight year term of copyright,
if you wanted a longer term of copyright,

00:34:49.620 --> 00:34:54.490
you had to file a renewal request with the
U.S. copyright office,

00:34:54.490 --> 00:34:57.120
and if you did that, you'd get another twenty-eight
years.

00:34:57.120 --> 00:35:01.960
So if you ask people now, you know, well,
you get a twenty-eight year monopoly and for

00:35:01.960 --> 00:35:04.820
three bucks
and filling out a simple government form,

00:35:04.820 --> 00:35:09.090
you're going to get another twenty-eight years,
most people, you would think, would

00:35:09.090 --> 00:35:10.090
say "yeah, sure.

00:35:10.090 --> 00:35:12.000
I'll take the other twenty-eight years.

00:35:12.000 --> 00:35:15.520
It doesn't harm me,
it's not a lot of work to do, the transactional

00:35:15.520 --> 00:35:18.020
costs aren't high to get the twenty-eight
years."

00:35:18.020 --> 00:35:22.360
But the actual data shows that most people
didn't do it.

00:35:22.360 --> 00:35:27.740
For almost a hundred years, the data was uniform
that the renewal rate was

00:35:27.740 --> 00:35:29.850
fifteen percent.

00:35:29.850 --> 00:35:34.470
Now this is actually a much smaller subset
of copyright works

00:35:34.470 --> 00:35:36.930
because most works were never registered in
the first place.

00:35:36.930 --> 00:35:41.370
And if you break it down
by type of work, motion pictures had the largest

00:35:41.370 --> 00:35:43.900
renewal rate seventy-four percent.

00:35:43.900 --> 00:35:46.930
Books had seven percent renewal rate, right?

00:35:46.930 --> 00:35:50.850
So ninety-three percent of the books,
the twenty-eight year term of copyright was

00:35:50.850 --> 00:35:51.850
quite enough.

00:35:51.850 --> 00:35:54.981
And it wasn't that
book publishers were lazy, it's that they

00:35:54.981 --> 00:36:00.510
made a rational economic decision
that the economic value of their work was

00:36:00.510 --> 00:36:02.390
over, after twenty-eight years.

00:36:02.390 --> 00:36:07.100
So in a rational system, you would take those
market signals, you wouldn't have one size

00:36:07.100 --> 00:36:09.970
fits all,
which doesn't make sense anyway, I mean if

00:36:09.970 --> 00:36:14.530
the market evidence shows you
that there's seven percent for books and seventy-four

00:36:14.530 --> 00:36:18.390
percent for motion pictures,
motion pictures might get a longer term than

00:36:18.390 --> 00:36:19.490
books would.

00:36:19.490 --> 00:36:24.970
But by having this requirement,
that you need to renew your interest in works,

00:36:24.970 --> 00:36:29.860
we cut out a lot of works where there
was no interest, and for those works where

00:36:29.860 --> 00:36:32.700
there was interest, you could go to those
people

00:36:32.700 --> 00:36:33.700
and license it.

00:36:33.700 --> 00:36:37.300
So I actually think, in response to your question,
it's a really great idea,

00:36:37.300 --> 00:36:39.080
and we should do it again.

00:36:39.080 --> 00:36:42.710
To go back to the trade policy issue, we can't,
