said "Only a blockhead would write for-"

00:41:58.360 --> 00:41:59.360
&gt;&gt;Bill: Johnson, Sam

00:41:59.360 --> 00:42:02.160
&gt;&gt;Fred: Samuel Johnson said "Only a blockhead
would write for free."

00:42:02.160 --> 00:42:06.200
Um, in fact, you find, lots of people
write for free for all kinds of reasons and

00:42:06.200 --> 00:42:07.200
&gt;&gt;Bill: Including him by the way

00:42:07.200 --> 00:42:09.340
&gt;&gt;Fred: Including him, exactly.

00:42:09.340 --> 00:42:13.000
You really want to test empirically, do you,
do publishers

00:42:13.000 --> 00:42:14.450
really need copyright?

00:42:14.450 --> 00:42:17.550
How do publishers do who don't use copyright?

00:42:17.550 --> 00:42:22.030
What actually happens in these markets
and a lot of the answers might be surprising,

00:42:22.030 --> 00:42:24.320
and if they're not surprising, I'd be happy
to learn that, too.

00:42:24.320 --> 00:42:28.420
&gt;&gt;Bill: It really is asking the questions,
not prejudging to say, "Oh, I really know

00:42:28.420 --> 00:42:30.050
copyright's not necessary."

00:42:30.050 --> 00:42:31.580
It is necessary for stuff.

00:42:31.580 --> 00:42:35.270
We've got to figure out what it's necessary
for, and what it's not.

00:42:35.270 --> 00:42:38.620
You know,
the intuitive stuff is where we get into trouble.

00:42:38.620 --> 00:42:41.790
I'd have these arguments with my mother, and
at the end,

00:42:41.790 --> 00:42:43.640
she'd say,"Don't confuse me with the facts."

00:42:43.640 --> 00:42:47.090
[laughter] And I'd go, I'd like to be confused
by them.

00:42:47.090 --> 00:42:48.530
&gt;&gt;Fred: Brad?

00:42:48.530 --> 00:42:53.760
&gt;&gt;Brad: Umm, I've,yes, as Fred knows, I've
written a bunch about this and there's sort

00:42:53.760 --> 00:42:58.100
of a, just to get to one question,
I do believe that the investors that are putting

00:42:58.100 --> 00:43:02.700
the hundreds of millions together
do actually want a copyright as their goal,

00:43:02.700 --> 00:43:05.770
as you said the writer isn't saying "today
I want to get a copyright,"

00:43:05.770 --> 00:43:08.720
but I think those investors actually are,
so there is a fair point to that.

00:43:08.720 --> 00:43:11.310
But I want to get
to one of the central issues that I haven't

00:43:11.310 --> 00:43:16.720
found a good solution for, and that is,
having a powerful fourth estate in a world

00:43:16.720 --> 00:43:18.090
without copyright.

00:43:18.090 --> 00:43:23.120
Um, you know, the Martha Grahams of the world,
who become billionaires on publishing, or

00:43:23.120 --> 00:43:26.310
the New York Times,
and then she is able to take on a president

00:43:26.310 --> 00:43:27.770
with her power.

00:43:27.770 --> 00:43:30.570
The huge money she made, she's able to take
on

00:43:30.570 --> 00:43:35.600
and take down a president using that power,
and the world of the blogosphere, where people

00:43:35.600 --> 00:43:37.790
will indeed
write news for free.

00:43:37.790 --> 00:43:42.080
They'll report the news, they'll cover things
that the major news media don't find,

00:43:42.080 --> 00:43:46.480
perform a very very valuable role, but having
powerful rich media who've been able

00:43:46.480 --> 00:43:50.590
to build a business empire based on selling
that information in the past,

00:43:50.590 --> 00:43:55.180
based, not so much on copyright when it was
not online, but today more based on it.

00:43:55.180 --> 00:43:59.100
How do we preserve
those, have those people that can be so rich

00:43:59.100 --> 00:44:02.890
by having that control, and then can take
on presidents and serve society?

00:44:02.890 --> 00:44:07.770
&gt;&gt;Bill: I think that the Washington Post makes
most of its money off of Kaplan.

00:44:07.770 --> 00:44:12.490
&gt;&gt;Brad: So, I am certain that's true, but
unless you want to claim that the news media

00:44:12.490 --> 00:44:16.350
make no use
of copyright, and do not, and are not in the

00:44:16.350 --> 00:44:22.120
in fact seeing their decline because
of their inability to use the same business

00:44:22.120 --> 00:44:24.130
models that they had in the paper world.

00:44:24.130 --> 00:44:29.920
&gt;&gt;Fred: It's intriguing, because I'm thinking,
