00:46:14.250 --> 00:46:19.810
&gt;&gt; male #3: I want to follow up on what you
said about making sure that content creators

00:46:19.810 --> 00:46:22.600
get paid, rather than make sure they have
exclusive rights.

00:46:22.600 --> 00:46:24.930
Now, it's fair to say I should read the book,
okay,

00:46:24.930 --> 00:46:29.910
so I'll accept that answer, but otherwise,
are you suggesting something like ASCAP or

00:46:29.910 --> 00:46:34.271
BMI where your stuff
is owned by some central agency that will

00:46:34.271 --> 00:46:37.370
license it for you and sends you a check periodically
or, or what?

00:46:37.370 --> 00:46:42.060
&gt;&gt;Bill: So there's a lot of discussion right
now about copyright registries,

00:46:42.060 --> 00:46:45.230
and about collective administration of rights.

00:46:45.230 --> 00:46:49.910
In Europe, they're already very far that way
in ways

00:46:49.910 --> 00:46:54.860
that maybe some people don't like so, if I'm
a composer in Europe, I have to license my

00:46:54.860 --> 00:46:58.240
work collectively,
I don't have the option, as I do here in the

00:46:58.240 --> 00:47:04.290
United States, of not going to ASCAP or BMI,
and doing it directly.

00:47:04.290 --> 00:47:11.840
There certainly have been issues of transparency
in some collecting societies in Europe,

00:47:11.840 --> 00:47:15.320
and even occasionally corruption, as well.

00:47:15.320 --> 00:47:20.090
With some Mediterranean societies being raided
by the police, [chuckles]

00:47:20.090 --> 00:47:22.750
and stuff like that.

00:47:22.750 --> 00:47:27.790
But the basic model for ASCAP and BMI I still
think makes sense.

00:47:27.790 --> 00:47:31.400
Which is that you,
as a creator, can't go around to every bar

00:47:31.400 --> 00:47:35.190
and restaurant or broadcaster throughout the
country

00:47:35.190 --> 00:47:36.190
&gt;&gt;Fred: Or website

00:47:36.190 --> 00:47:38.540
&gt;&gt;Bill: Or website and spend your time licensing.

00:47:38.540 --> 00:47:43.280
It's really an issue for, say, photographers,
as well.

00:47:43.280 --> 00:47:48.900
My point is that, yeah, we do need to go to
something like that, simply because it's the

00:47:48.900 --> 00:47:53.760
only probable way
that people can get paid.

00:47:53.760 --> 00:47:58.950
And one of the things that many people are
working on the registry area is,

00:47:58.950 --> 00:48:02.550
of course, something that we do very well,
which is building a data base.

00:48:02.550 --> 00:48:04.090
&gt;&gt;Fred: Just a, just

00:48:04.090 --> 00:48:09.180
&gt;&gt;Bill: mm, who, who owns what rights?That's
got to be the first thing, who owns the rights?

00:48:09.180 --> 00:48:14.840
What are the terms of it, is it time limited,
is it regionally limited,

00:48:14.840 --> 00:48:17.660
is it limited to the sound recording, not
the musical thing.

00:48:17.660 --> 00:48:21.310
So I know there are
a lot of people doing a lot of work on that

00:48:21.310 --> 00:48:24.870
and I think it's an idea that has come to
be accepted

00:48:24.870 --> 00:48:27.110
by a lot of content owners as well.

00:48:27.110 --> 00:48:31.120
That the only way we're going to get people
paid is to first build a data base

00:48:31.120 --> 00:48:36.990
of who owns what, and then it can be cleared
and then the second step is the sort of automatically

00:48:36.990 --> 00:48:38.560
licensing thing that
you're talking about.

00:48:38.560 --> 00:48:42.510
I mean CCC paved the way for a lot of that
step.

00:48:42.510 --> 00:48:45.810
&gt;&gt;Fred: That's Copyright Clearance Center
here in the United States.

00:48:45.810 --> 00:48:50.620
&gt;&gt;Bill: Yep, and also Creative Commons has
done a lot of work concerning those.

00:48:50.620 --> 00:48:52.030
So I think it's a two step thing.

00:48:52.030 --> 00:48:56.760
The first step is building a database of who
owns what, and the second step is using that

00:48:56.760 --> 00:49:00.220
database
to allow people to license things, or setting

00:49:00.220 --> 00:49:04.000
up micropayments, or other ways of doing it.

00:49:04.000 --> 00:49:06.830
There are a lot of people
who are doing work on that, even at Google

00:49:06.830 --> 00:49:07.830
too.

00:49:07.830 --> 00:49:10.660
&gt;&gt;Fred: And there's a, I just want to point
out, there's a lot of situations where that

00:49:10.660 --> 00:49:13.360
kind of solution
happens already.

00:49:13.360 --> 00:49:18.720
And, uh, YouTube comes to mind for example,
where the major record labels,

00:49:18.720 --> 00:49:23.550
and a number of independents as well, have
granted YouTube licenses essentially to their

00:49:23.550 --> 00:49:26.320
entire catalogs,
there's some exceptions and this and that,

00:49:26.320 --> 00:49:30.740
but the general way it works is that, you
know, a user,

00:49:30.740 --> 00:49:37.190
a YouTube user can upload a video with a song
as the soundtrack without the user having

00:49:37.190 --> 00:49:40.660
to figure out
who owns it, without clearances, without any

00:49:40.660 --> 00:49:42.890
of those transactional headaches.

00:49:42.890 --> 00:49:47.530
The rights holder is compensated
based on advertising that appears around the

00:49:47.530 --> 00:49:52.970
video, and that is, in a way, a sort of collective
approach,

00:49:52.970 --> 00:49:59.420
almost like a blanket license that works well
enough in practice to actually be a win for

00:49:59.420 --> 00:50:00.420
everybody.

00:50:00.420 --> 00:50:03.850
A win for users who get to post what they
like, a win for rights holders who get paid,

00:50:03.850 --> 00:50:07.120
and it's a win for Google
because we get a piece of that revenue as

00:50:07.120 --> 00:50:08.120
well.

00:50:08.120 --> 00:50:12.150
So, some of that can happen without waiting
for, I agree,

00:50:12.150 --> 00:50:16.980
it is ridiculous that it is so difficult to
figure out who owns what, and we do need to

00:50:16.980 --> 00:50:18.110
solve that problem.

00:50:18.110 --> 00:50:23.940
But we don't need to wait for the perfect
utopian registry in order to get started.

00:50:23.940 --> 00:50:24.940
&gt;&gt;Bill: Right.

00:50:24.940 --> 00:50:26.920
&gt;&gt;Fred: We need to get there, but at the same
time.

00:50:26.920 --> 00:50:27.920
Other-

00:50:27.920 --> 00:50:33.960
&gt;&gt;Bill: We are participating in European Union
GRD, the Global Rights Database, and there's

00:50:33.960 --> 00:50:38.840
been a lot of work done
internally on that, with rights holders to

00:50:38.840 --> 00:50:40.700
make it happen.

