00:50:42.930 --> 00:50:48.490
&gt;&gt;female #1: How do you feel about the Twin
Books Ruling for the Ninth Circuit Court?

00:50:48.490 --> 00:50:49.490
Is that even--

00:50:49.490 --> 00:50:50.490
&gt;&gt;Bill: Insane.

00:50:50.490 --> 00:50:51.490
&gt;&gt;female#1: Insane?

00:50:51.490 --> 00:50:52.490
Okay, I am glad I am not alone in that!

00:50:52.490 --> 00:50:55.250
&gt;&gt;Fred: For the benefit of the audience, you
might want to say a little bit about what

00:50:55.250 --> 00:50:56.640
Twin Books is and why

00:50:56.640 --> 00:51:00.000
&gt;&gt;Bill: Well, Fred is an old Ninth Circuit
Clerk of course

00:51:00.000 --> 00:51:01.950
&gt;&gt;Fred: Not my fault.

00:51:01.950 --> 00:51:03.690
It wasn't decided when I was there.

00:51:03.690 --> 00:51:04.690
[laughter]

00:51:04.690 --> 00:51:05.690
&gt;&gt;Bill: Yeah, right, right.

00:51:05.690 --> 00:51:11.420
So here's the, this is highly technical issue
but it's how Fred and I make a living,

00:51:11.420 --> 00:51:14.750
so, you can't begrudge us that, I hope.

00:51:14.750 --> 00:51:16.910
So here's the issue.

00:51:16.910 --> 00:51:24.950
There was under a prior law,
the 1909 Act, a requirement that for a foreign

00:51:24.950 --> 00:51:29.470
work to be subject to copyright, you had to
put a copyright notice

00:51:29.470 --> 00:51:30.470
on it.

00:51:30.470 --> 00:51:33.250
Now we were the only county in the world that
had that requirement

00:51:33.250 --> 00:51:36.760
&gt;&gt;Fred: That's the, That's the "C" in a circle
with your name and date.

00:51:36.760 --> 00:51:39.100
&gt;&gt;Bill: the "C" in a circle and copyright
date, or like the motion pictures did, they

00:51:39.100 --> 00:51:42.510
used the Roman letters
so you can't figure out what year it is.

00:51:42.510 --> 00:51:45.540
I still can't figure out what year it is,
but they're doing it so that

00:51:45.540 --> 00:51:50.960
they comply with it, but nobody knows this
was last year's movie, right, right.

00:51:50.960 --> 00:51:52.230
That's the purpose for that.

00:51:52.230 --> 00:51:58.210
Um so, yeah,even though I studied Latin in
school, I still can't figure it out.

00:51:58.210 --> 00:52:02.120
So there's this requirement,
that if you were a German author, you need,

00:52:02.120 --> 00:52:05.970
you needed to have put that notice on it.

00:52:05.970 --> 00:52:08.720
If you put it on, then things
were great.

00:52:08.720 --> 00:52:13.650
You had a copyright in the United States,
leaving aside other things like the manufacturing

00:52:13.650 --> 00:52:16.270
clause,
but you had your copyright in the United States.

00:52:16.270 --> 00:52:18.370
That was true for U.S. authors, too, by the
way.

00:52:18.370 --> 00:52:23.470
We had to put a copyright notice on, and if
we didn't, it went into the public domain,

00:52:23.470 --> 00:52:25.410
meaning there was no copyright.

00:52:25.410 --> 00:52:31.530
So, what happened if a foreign work didn't
put that copyright notice on,

00:52:31.530 --> 00:52:32.600
the EASY answer--

00:52:32.600 --> 00:52:33.610
&gt;&gt;Fred: And it was published overseas?

00:52:33.610 --> 00:52:36.480
&gt;&gt;Bill: It was published overseas.

00:52:36.480 --> 00:52:41.530
The easy answer, the textual answer would
be, it's in the public domain too

00:52:41.530 --> 00:52:47.780
right, after all, if you get copyright by
doing it, and you don't do it, then the logical

00:52:47.780 --> 00:52:51.930
thing is you suffer
the consequences because you got the good

00:52:51.930 --> 00:52:54.380
and that's what the statute says.

00:52:54.380 --> 00:52:58.300
That, of course, is not
what the Ninth Circuit did.

00:52:58.300 --> 00:53:04.630
They created this sort of weird hybrid which
is that, well,

00:53:04.630 --> 00:53:11.690
it wasn't protected, but it wasn't unprotected
quite either.

00:53:11.690 --> 00:53:15.450
And so that has caused lots of problems.

00:53:15.450 --> 00:53:19.290
One of them is, causes problems for anyone
trying to figure out whether a foreign work

00:53:19.290 --> 00:53:21.660
is in the public domain or not.

00:53:21.660 --> 00:53:25.480
It also caused problems, because when I worked
for Congress in 1994,

00:53:25.480 --> 00:53:33.190
we passed this law, the GATT, General Agreement
on Tariffs and Trades, which took out,

00:53:33.190 --> 00:53:39.380
from the public domain, these foreign works
that hadn't complied that obligation.

00:53:39.380 --> 00:53:44.730
And, that was upheld by the Supreme Court
quite recently.

00:53:44.730 --> 00:53:49.260
I know a lot of people don't like it,
but I personally was relieved that a statute

00:53:49.260 --> 00:53:51.410
that I wrote wasn't found unconstitutional.

00:53:51.410 --> 00:53:54.540
Small matter of pride.

00:53:54.540 --> 00:54:01.700
[laughter] Not a popular one within the company,
but you know, it was my own.

00:54:01.700 --> 00:54:03.710
So that law actually took care
of the situation.

00:54:03.710 --> 00:54:08.320
It said, "look if you are this foreign person
and you didn't really realize it, it's okay,

00:54:08.320 --> 00:54:11.650
we're giving it back to you and you have the
same term of protection you would have otherwise

00:54:11.650 --> 00:54:13.910
had."

00:54:13.910 --> 00:54:16.210
But no,
that's not what the Ninth Circuit did, and

00:54:16.210 --> 00:54:18.070
that's a problem that we live with a lot.

00:54:18.070 --> 00:54:19.660
&gt;&gt;Fred: Yeah, the Google Books team

00:54:19.660 --> 00:54:21.450
&gt;&gt;Bill: How do you engineer that?

