&gt;&gt;Bill: I think what you are referring to
is this chapter twelve, and title seventeen

00:55:23.850 --> 00:55:28.050
is really technically
not a copyright thing, but it's used that

00:55:28.050 --> 00:55:31.160
way, and I agree with your point.

00:55:31.160 --> 00:55:35.930
The point would say,
I can engage in satire and parody because

00:55:35.930 --> 00:55:41.610
it's fair use, but if there's this code, that's
deemed a

00:55:41.610 --> 00:55:47.550
technological protection measure and I need
to break that code to engage in parody or

00:55:47.550 --> 00:55:50.230
fair use,
it's an independent violation.

00:55:50.230 --> 00:55:55.180
&gt;&gt;Fred: This is the classic reason why you
can rip your own CDs onto your IPod, but you

00:55:55.180 --> 00:55:56.770
can't rip
your DVDs onto your IPod.

00:55:56.770 --> 00:55:57.770
&gt;&gt;Bill: Right.

00:55:57.770 --> 00:56:02.521
&gt;&gt;Fred: Because the latter, DVDs, have a technological
protection measure, and you would have to

00:56:02.521 --> 00:56:06.220
break it
in order to copy it onto your IPod so, different

00:56:06.220 --> 00:56:07.220
answer.

00:56:07.220 --> 00:56:10.150
&gt;&gt;Bill: I mean, the greatest use of it, as
Fred and I were talking about earlier today,

00:56:10.150 --> 00:56:15.410
is not for that sort of stuff,
but in controlling consumer product features.

00:56:15.410 --> 00:56:18.310
That's how it was originally written, and
to me, it's sort of, it's very

00:56:18.310 --> 00:56:24.210
medieval, it's like medieval moats and stuff,
and it's like giving someone, like giving

00:56:24.210 --> 00:56:28.210
some guy the right to put a chastity
belt on somebody else's wife, you know.

00:56:28.210 --> 00:56:29.750
It doesn't really make sense.

00:56:29.750 --> 00:56:33.670
[laughter] I mean , copyright
has always had to do with technology, this

00:56:33.670 --> 00:56:37.910
is true, but it's always dealt with a use
of technology

00:56:37.910 --> 00:56:42.810
positively or negatively, with the ultimate
consumer or the author.

00:56:42.810 --> 00:56:48.710
And what these anti-circumvention things do
sort of cross the Rubicon, to use another

00:56:48.710 --> 00:56:54.050
ancient metaphor, of giving control over what
third parties do.

00:56:54.050 --> 00:56:57.160
And, personally, I would love to have those
repealed.

00:56:57.160 --> 00:57:03.070
I think they don't make sense, but again,
they are in so many trade agreements now,

00:57:03.070 --> 00:57:04.070
that it would be really hard.

00:57:04.070 --> 00:57:07.170
Let's say that we just
decided we were wrong and it's really a stupid

00:57:07.170 --> 00:57:13.110
thing to do, it's anti-consumer,
it harms markets, it harms like everything

00:57:13.110 --> 00:57:15.140
it touches, it's radioactive.

00:57:15.140 --> 00:57:17.250
There's nothing we can do
about it.

00:57:17.250 --> 00:57:22.160
Because we'd have to abrogate all these treaty
agreements, and that's a huge problem.

00:57:22.160 --> 00:57:26.530
They're not only anti-democratic, but they
stop us from fixing our mistakes.

00:57:26.530 --> 00:57:30.890
&gt;&gt;Fred: So I think we're about, do we have
time for one more?

00:57:30.890 --> 00:57:31.890
&gt;&gt;male #5: Yeah.

00:57:31.890 --> 00:57:32.890
&gt;&gt;Fred: Great.

00:57:32.890 --> 00:57:36.320
&gt;&gt;male #6: Okay, I have a question that segues
off this but also gets back

00:57:36.320 --> 00:57:39.060
to an earlier discussion around creativity.

00:57:39.060 --> 00:57:44.480
Just, I have a number of friends who are deejays,
and video editors, and a big trend, especially

00:57:44.480 --> 00:57:50.200
on YouTube, is to kind of take existing songs
out there and mash them up and remix them,

00:57:50.200 --> 00:57:52.791
in a way where you actually create a new work,
and as well

00:57:52.791 --> 00:57:54.910
with video as well.

00:57:54.910 --> 00:58:00.500
And I was wondering what your thoughts are
on perhaps on how we could help move

00:58:00.500 --> 00:58:06.150
copyright law into an area where it would
kind work in this new digital environment

00:58:06.150 --> 00:58:12.290
where
well, just for an example, when a friend uploads

00:58:12.290 --> 00:58:18.210
his video to YouTube, sometimes it will say
we've found that you're using five different

00:58:18.210 --> 00:58:22.800
samples from these songs, and it will recognize
who owns the rights.

00:58:22.800 --> 00:58:27.890
But then sometimes it will prohibit him from
uploading the video at all, and sometimes

00:58:27.890 --> 00:58:31.650
there will be some kind of cost sharing program
going on.

00:58:31.650 --> 00:58:35.900
But I was curious as to what do you sort of
recommend

00:58:35.900 --> 00:58:38.280
for these remix and mash up works?

00:58:38.280 --> 00:58:41.900
&gt;&gt;Bill: The Canadian Reform Bill actually
has a provision on this

00:58:41.900 --> 00:58:43.220
&gt;&gt;Fred: I was going to say move to Canada

00:58:43.220 --> 00:58:45.320
&gt;&gt;Bill: Move to Canada, yeah.

00:58:45.320 --> 00:58:48.530
And you'll also have notice and notice, not
notice and take down.

00:58:48.530 --> 00:58:50.360
That's the second part of
that.

00:58:50.360 --> 00:58:57.280
They actually have proposed a specific provision
for user generated content that's non-commercial,

00:58:57.280 --> 00:58:59.130
and really
addresses this issue.

00:58:59.130 --> 00:59:03.410
&gt;&gt;Fred: But, under U.S. law, wouldn't you
say that fair use often could address the

00:59:03.410 --> 00:59:04.410
issue already?

00:59:04.410 --> 00:59:05.410
&gt;&gt;Bill: Yes, yes.

00:59:05.410 --> 00:59:11.520
But then there's the nice intersection between
video content and ID.

00:59:11.520 --> 00:59:12.630
&gt;&gt;Fred: Well, that's right.

00:59:12.630 --> 00:59:21.790
On YouTube, when content ID detects a match,
the content owner can ask for that to be blocked.

00:59:21.790 --> 00:59:25.240
Which is why your friend is seeing things
not get uploaded.

00:59:25.240 --> 00:59:30.000
Those matches can be overridden by the user
disputing it,

00:59:30.000 --> 00:59:33.790
and at that point the rights holder can then
send a take down notice formally if they believe

00:59:33.790 --> 00:59:36.710
it's infringing,
and the user has a right to submit a counter

00:59:36.710 --> 00:59:38.790
notice under our DMCA.

00:59:38.790 --> 00:59:42.210
So it's a very complicated system, but it
certainly

00:59:42.210 --> 00:59:45.610
offers more than a system that would simply
prohibit it.

00:59:45.610 --> 00:59:48.250
Which frankly, a lot of copyright laws around
the world

00:59:48.250 --> 00:59:51.900
leave no room that kind of creativity at all.

00:59:51.900 --> 00:59:56.200
Which is part of the reason why, I think in
many ways the United States,

00:59:56.200 --> 00:59:58.670
now perhaps Canada, there are a number of
countries

00:59:58.670 --> 01:00:02.790
&gt;&gt;Bill: Israel
&gt;&gt;Fred: Israel, um, a lot of this creativity

01:00:02.790 --> 01:00:05.450
at least has room in those systems.

01:00:05.450 --> 01:00:11.610
Interestingly, the U.K. just completed
a big study led by a professor named Ian Hargreaves

01:00:11.610 --> 01:00:14.240
that describes how they think their copyright
law might

01:00:14.240 --> 01:00:19.370
need to change in order accommodate that sort
of creativity so there is, in some ways, it

01:00:19.370 --> 01:00:21.700
may not be perfect,
but the United States is a little bit in the

01:00:21.700 --> 01:00:23.780
vanguard when it comes to that sort of thing.

01:00:23.780 --> 01:00:27.730
&gt;&gt;Bill: The other concept we should deal with
is that in addition to fair use, which we

01:00:27.730 --> 01:00:29.360
have, is derivative works.

01:00:29.360 --> 01:00:33.270
The scope of derivative works because that's
part of what you're talking about.

01:00:33.270 --> 01:00:41.000
And I think, a different look
at derivative works, limiting them to market

01:00:41.000 --> 01:00:42.650
displacement.

01:00:42.650 --> 01:00:46.160
You would give a right to procure
derivative works so for example if I write

01:00:46.160 --> 01:00:49.130
a, go back and I write a novel, someone wants
to make a movie out of it

01:00:49.130 --> 01:00:53.530
that's a derivative work and I should have
the right to control that, or someone wants

01:00:53.530 --> 01:00:59.060
to use my song in a film or
a political advertisement, you know, those

01:00:59.060 --> 01:01:00.060
sort of things.

01:01:00.060 --> 01:01:03.820
But derivative works that are themselves,
what we would say, transformative,

01:01:03.820 --> 01:01:10.510
creative and that don't harm the market for
the original, is a concept that probably should

01:01:10.510 --> 01:01:13.090
be revisited, I think.

01:01:13.090 --> 01:01:20.730
And there are, of course, even with content
and ideas, there are a lot of companies that

01:01:20.730 --> 01:01:21.870
do permit it.

01:01:21.870 --> 01:01:22.900
&gt;&gt;Fred: Absolutely right.

01:01:22.900 --> 01:01:27.180
&gt;&gt;Bill: So it's not a monolithic, you know,
that all big companies are trying to suppress

01:01:27.180 --> 01:01:28.600
this stuff.

01:01:28.600 --> 01:01:30.870
There
are a number of them that allow parody and

01:01:30.870 --> 01:01:33.560
a number of them allow mash ups, too.

01:01:33.560 --> 01:01:36.960
&gt;&gt;Fred: So I think that brings us to an end
here.

01:01:36.960 --> 01:01:38.600
I want to thank Bill for coming by.

01:01:38.600 --> 01:01:40.190
&gt;&gt;Bill: Thank you everyone for coming too.

